all>([[Master of Divinity|M.Div.]])</small>}}<br>[[American University]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]])</small>\n| occupation         =\n| profession         = Professor, politician\n| religion           = Christian<!-- see talk page before changing this -->\n| signature          =\n| website            = http://brat.house.gov/\n}}\n\n'''David Alan''' \"'''Dave'''\" '''Brat''' (born July 27, 1964) is an American  [[economist]] and member of the [[United States House of Representatives]], serving [[Virginia's 7th congressional district]] since 2014.  Prior to his election to Congress, Brat was a professor at [[Randolph\u2013Macon College]]. A Republican, he serves on these House Committees: Budget, Education and Workforce, and Small Business.\n\nBrat defeated [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Majority Leader]] [[Eric Cantor]] in the district's 2014 Republican primary on June 10, 2014.<ref name=DallasNews20140610>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/national-politics/20140610-house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-loses-gop-primary-to-tea-party-challenger.ece |title=House Majority Leader Eric Cantor loses GOP primary to tea-party challenger |work=Dallas Morning News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat's primary victory over Cantor made him the first primary challenger to oust a sitting House Majority Leader since the position's creation in 1899, and is considered one of the biggest upsets in congressional history.<ref>{{cite news |author=Eric Linton |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-defeated-tea-party-challenger-david-brat-virginia-gop-1597736 |title=House Majority Leader Eric Cantor Defeated By Tea Party Challenger David Brat In Virginia GOP Primary |publisher=International Business Times |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Jack Trammell]], a fellow professor at Randolph-Macon College, and [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] nominee James Carr on November 4, 2014.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBrat was born in Detroit<ref>{{cite news |author=Gary Robertson |date=May 2014 |url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/articles/dave-brat-republican-primary.html?page=2 |title=News and Features |work=Richmond Magazine |accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref> on July 27, 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/article/533729|title=Virginia-7: Dave Brat (R)|work=nationaljournal.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Elizabeth Nolan Brown |date=June 11, 2014 |url=http://reason.com/24-7/2014/06/11/dave-brat-the-man-who-beat-eric-cantor |title=Who Is Dave Brat? Take a Look at the Ayn Rand Loving, Immigration Reform Hating, Cato Institute Referencing Man Who Beat Eric Cantor \u2013 Reason 24/7 |publisher=Reason.com |accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref> Brat's father, Paul, was a Doctor of [[internal medicine|Internal Medicine]]; his mother, Nancy, was employed as a [[social worker]] in [[Alma, Michigan]], where he was raised.<ref name=\"themorningsun1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.themorningsun.com/government-and-politics/20140611/alma-native-now-in-the-red-hot-heat-of-publicity |title=Alma native now in the red hot heat of publicity |publisher=Themorningsun.com |date=2014-06-06 |accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref><ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Juanski |date=June 11, 2014 |url=http://michigan.icito.com/tag/david-brat/ |title=David Brat Archives &#124; Michigan News |publisher=Michigan.icito.com |accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/articles/dave-brat-republican-primary.html |title=News and Features |work=Richmond Magazine |date=2013-12-07 |accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref> His family moved from Alma to Minnesota when David, the oldest of three boys, was in junior high.<ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/> Brat graduated from [[Park Center Senior High School]] in [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/>\n\nBrat attended [[Hope College]] in Michigan and received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Business Administration in 1986; he also graduated with a [[Master's degree|Master's Degree]] in Divinity from [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] in 1990 and earned a Ph.D in economics from [[American University]] in 1995.<ref name=education>{{cite web |title=Academic CV |author=David Brat |publisher=Randolph-Macon College |url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/BRAT2012-CV.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nAfter working for [[Arthur Andersen]] and as a consultant for the [[World Bank]], Brat joined the faculty of [[Randolph\u2013Macon College]] in 1996,<ref name=education/> where he served as chair of the department of economics, and taught courses including \"Britain in the International Economy\", \"International Economic Development\", and \"Business Ethics\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/classes.html |title=Classes |publisher=Randolph-Macon College |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012 Brat headed Randolph-Macon's BB&T Moral Foundations of Capitalism program, one of sixty similar programs and chairs in the philosophy and economics departments at United States universities devoted to the study of capitalism and morality, endowed by the [[BB&T Corporation]].<ref name=Newsweek_Pema>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Pema |date=June 11, 2014 |title=What We Know About Dave Brat, the Tea Party Candidate Who Beat Eric Cantor |url=http://www.newsweek.com/dave-brat-beat-eric-cantor-and-hes-probably-headed-congress-254551 |publisher=Newsweek |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=YahooBBT>{{cite news |date=June 13, 2014 |last=Santoli |first=Michael |title=The big bank that blessed Brat's upset of Eric Cantor |url=http://finance.yahoo.com/blogs/breakout/the-big-bank-that-blessed-brat-s-upset-of-eric-cantor-125146311.html |publisher=Yahoo Finance |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clemson.edu/capitalism/capres/bbtp.html |title=Clemson Institute for the Study of Capitalism |publisher=Clemson University |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=RMC-CV>{{cite web|title=David Brat Faculty CV|url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/2012professionalActivity.html|website=Randolph-Macon College|publisher=Randolph-Macon College|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Brat was appointed by Virginia governor [[Tim Kaine]] to the Governor's Advisory Board of Economists, a position he continues to hold. He has also served on the board of directors of the [[Richmond Metropolitan Authority]], and on the advisory board of the Virginia Public Access Project.<ref name=\"RMC-CV\"/>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Special legislative assistant===\nFrom 2005 to 2011, Brat worked as a special [[legislative assistant]] to Virginia state senator [[Walter Stosch]] in the area of [[higher education]].<ref name=education/> In 2006 he was appointed by Democratic governor [[Tim Kaine]] to serve on a bipartisan economic advisory council. He was later reappointed by Republican Governor [[Bob McDonnell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsmax.com/Politics/Cantor-defeat-reason-Brat/2014/06/10/id/576307/|title=Virginians Felt Cantor's DC Power Did Little to Help Them|last=Gizzi|first=John|date=June 10, 2014|work=NewsMax|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2011 campaign for Virginia's 56th House of Delegates seat===\nIn August 2011, Brat announced he was running for the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] seat for the 56th district. There was no primary, and six Republican leaders met and chose [[Peter Farrell (politician)|Peter Farrell]], as the Republican nominee in the November 2011 general election.<ref>{{cite web |author=Michelle Stanley |date=August 18, 2011 |publisher=Virginia Right |url=http://www.varight.com/news/dr-david-brat-seeks-56th-house-of-delegate-seat/ |title=Dr. David Brat seeks 56th House of Delegate Seat |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014 race for 7th congressional district===\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2014#District 7}}\n\n====Republican primary====\nBrat ran against House Majority Leader Eric Cantor for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nomination for [[Virginia's 7th congressional district]] and defeated Cantor by a 12-point margin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/06/10/house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-loses-virginia-gop-primary-ap-reports/|title=Cantor upset in Virginia GOP primary by Tea Party backed challenger|work=Fox News|author=Chad Pergram, Associated Press.|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat was outspent by Cantor 40 to 1: Cantor spent over $5 million, while Brat raised $200,000 and did not spend all of it.<ref name=\"MemoliLATimes06112014\">{{cite news |last=Memoli |first=Michael A. |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-eric-cantor-dave-brat-primary-20140611-story.html |title=Eric Cantor upset: How Dave Brat pulled off a historic political coup] |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mascaro |first=Lisa |author2=Michael A. Memoli |author3=Mark Z. Barabak |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-na-pn-cantor-loses-to-tea-party-challenger-20140610-story.html |title=Washington reels as House's Eric Cantor loses to tea party challenger |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> Brat's primary campaign was managed by 23-year-old Zachary Werrell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/meet-dave-brats-23-year-old-campaign-manager/article/2549565 |title=Meet Dave Brat's 23 Year Old Campaign Manager |work=Washington Examiner |author= Betsy Woodruff |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>  An analysis of campaign filings conducted by the [[Center for Responsive Politics]] concluded that Brat did not receive any donations from [[political action committees]] and ultimately conceded, \"it's almost impossible to profile Brat's typical donor, because he had so few.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2014/06/dave-versus-goliath-by-the-numbers/ |title=Dave Versus Goliath, By the Numbers |last=Choma |first=Russ |date=June 11, 2014 |website=opensecrets.org |publisher=Center for Responsive Politics |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat's win was a historic and stunning victory,<ref name=NYT06102014>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/11/us/politics/eric-cantor-loses-gop-primary.html |title=Eric Cantor Defeated by David Brat, Tea Party Challenger, in G.O.P. Primary Upset |work=The New York Times |last=Martin |first=Jonathan |date=June 11, 2014 |page=A1 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/no-2-house-republican-eric-cantor-defeated-in-virginia-primary-upset-1402445714|title=Eric Cantor Loses to Tea Party's David Brat in Virginia Primary|work=The Wall Street Journal|author=Janet Hook and Kristina Peterson|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/eric-cantor-faces-tea-party-challenge-tuesday/2014/06/10/17da5d20-f092-11e3-bf76-447a5df6411f_story.html|title=Eric Cantor succumbs to tea party challenger Tuesday|work=The Washington Post|author= Robert Costa, Laura Vozzella and David A. Fahrenthold|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> as it was the first time a sitting House Majority Leader was defeated in his primary race since the position was created in 1899.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/washington-is-caught-totally-off-guard-by-cantor-loss-023046579.html |title=Washington is caught totally off guard by Cantor loss |work=Yahoo News |author= Chris Moody |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCompared with Cantor, described as aloof, Brat was characterized as knowing how to work a crowd.<ref>J.S.,  [http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2014/06/virginia-politics \"Who Is David Brat?\"], Democracy in America blog, ''[[The Economist]]'',  June 16, 2014.  Retrieved October 29, 2014.</ref> He ran an anti-establishment campaign criticizing government bailouts and budget deals while frequently invoking God and the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] in his speeches. During the campaign, Cantor criticized Brat as a \"liberal professor\" who had strong ties to [[Tim Kaine]], Virginia's former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] governor and current junior Senator.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/208922-cantor-goes-down-to-tea-party-upset |title=Cantor out in Tea Party shocker |date=June 10, 2014 |website=thehill.com |publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)]] |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat ran well to Cantor's right, complaining that Cantor had a \"[[crony capitalism|crony-capitalist]] mentality\", putting the interests of the corporate sector ahead of small businesses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parkinson |first=John |title=Dave Brat: Meet the Candidate Who Beat Eric Cantor |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dave-brat-meet-candidate-beat-eric-cantor/story?id=24081628 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Radio talk show]] host [[Laura Ingraham]] endorsed Brat's candidacy and hosted a rally with him in a Richmond suburb.<ref name=DallasNews20140610/> Brat was also supported by radio talk show host [[Mark Levin]]<ref name=NY-11.6.14>{{cite news |last=Cassidy |first=John |title=Cantor Loses, and Washington Goes Ape |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/06/eric-cantor-loses-to-david-brat.html|accessdate=June 11, 2014|publisher=The New Yorker|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> and [[Ann Coulter]].<ref name=\"WP-Bump 10.6.14\">{{cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |title=David Brat just beat Eric Cantor. Who is he?|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/david-brat-just-beat-eric-cantor-who-is-he/|accessdate=June 11, 2014|publisher=The Washington Post|date=June 10, 2014}}</ref> [[Chris Peace]], a state legislator who collaborated with Brat on state budget issues at Randolph-Macon College, stated that Brat was inspired to run for Congress because of \"His passion for the structure of government and belief in free markets.\"<ref name=NYT140612>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/us/politics/david-brat-waged-solo-fight-against-eric-cantor.html |title=Once Snubbed, David Brat Turns the Tables |last=Steinhauer |first=Jennifer |date=June 12, 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat's victory was described in the press as exposing a \"deep schism\" in the Republican party between its conservative base and its business wing, as well as a split between establishment Republicans and [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party insurgents]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Matea|last=Gold|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How national tea party groups missed the David Brat boat |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/how-national-tea-party-groups-missed-the-david-brat-boat/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014|quote=Brat's victory underlined the deep schism in the party between its conservative base and its business wing. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tea party stuns GOP leader Eric Cantor|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/06/10/4968350/tea-party-stuns-gop-leader-eric.html#.U5s5By8Wdt8|publisher=Charlotte Observer|accessdate=June 13, 2014|quote=Brat also got help from the more conservative wing of the Virginia Republican Party, which for years has been split between more establishment Republicans and tea party activists.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Emboldened after Cantor, tea party crows|url=http://news.yahoo.com/emboldened-cantor-tea-party-crows-202904376--election.html |publisher=Yahoo News |accessdate=June 13, 2014|quote=The GOP is expected to retain control of the House, but Brat's pounding of Cantor Tuesday ripped open the establishment-vs.-insurgent split that's plagued the party since the 2010 elections.}}</ref> Some libertarian oriented groups backed Brat like the Virginia Liberty Party.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Virginia Liberty Party 2014 General Election Endorsements|url=http://www.virginialibertyparty.com/2014/11/the-virginia-liberty-party-2014-general.html |website=Virginia Liberty Party |accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat received support from, and gave credit for his win to, local Tea Party groups in Virginia, but received no funding or endorsement from national Tea Party organizations.<ref name=NYT06102014/> Brat has not self-identified with the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref>{{cite news |first=|last=|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How David Brat Won |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/2014-virginia-primary-david-brat-107700_Page2.html |work=[[Politico]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> Ron Rapoport, a political scientist at the [[College of William & Mary]], has said Brat may be correctly identified as a \"tea partier\" only if the term is used as a catchall for \"anti-establishment activist\", while [[John Judis]] has opined that Brat could more correctly be described as a \"[[right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Grier |last=Peter |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Is David Brat really a tea partier? |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/DC-Decoder/Decoder-Buzz/2014/0611/Is-David-Brat-really-a-tea-partyer-video |work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> [[Matea Gold]] in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' stated, \"the fact that Brat took off without the help of those organizations [national tea party groups] now makes it harder for them to claim his victory as their own.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Matea|last=Gold|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How national tea party groups missed the David Brat boat |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/how-national-tea-party-groups-missed-the-david-brat-boat/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the national media were shocked at Brat's victory, Richmond-area media outlets had received signs well before the primary that Cantor was in trouble.<ref name=Blindspot>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/16/business/media/eric-cantors-defeat-exposed-a-beltway-journalism-blind-spot.html|title=Eric Cantor\u2019s Defeat Exposed a Beltway Journalism Blind Spot|last=Carr|first=David|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=2014-06-16}}</ref>  The ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'' reported two weeks before the primary that a number of Cantor's constituents felt he took them for granted.  The ''Times-Dispatch'' also revealed that Cantor's attempt to brand Brat as a liberal professor actually made more people turn out for Brat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/state-regional/virginia-politics/schapiro-in-new-kent-brat-backers-hope-to-hold-cantor/article_dff230e0-d76a-599d-992e-3bb000efe560.html|title=In New Kent, Brat Backers Hope To Hold Cantor Accountable|last=Schapiro|first=Jeff|publisher=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|date=2014-05-24}}</ref>  ''The Chesterfield Observer,'' a local paper serving [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]]\u2014roughly half of which is in the 7th\u2014reported that Tea Party-aligned candidates had won several victories there, and at least one Cantor loyalist believed Tea Party supporters smelled \"blood in the water.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chesterfieldobserver.com/news/2014-06-04/Front_Page/Retreading_the_GOP.html|title=Retreading the GOP?|last=McConnell|first=Jim|publisher=The Chesterfield Observer|date=2014-06-04}}</ref>  One local reporter told David Carr of ''[[The New York Times]]'' that many constituents believed Cantor was arrogant and unapproachable. However, due to massive cutbacks, the race was severely underpolled by local media.  Few Capitol Hill reporters were willing to go to Cantor's district, for fear that they would be out of Washington in case a major story broke.<ref name=Blindspot/>\n\nDuring an interview with [[Sean Hannity]] on the night of his win, Brat said:\n<blockquote>\nAnd I was blessed. I mean, it's a miracle. What do I attribute it to? First of all, I attribute it to God. And I'm utterly humbled and thankful. I'm a believer and so I'm humbled that God gave us this win. But right with that, God acts through people, and God acted through the people on my behalf.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hannity|first1=Sean|last2=Brat|first2=Dave|title=Dave Brat reacts to upset win over Eric Cantor in Virginia Republican primary|url=http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/hannity/transcript/2014/06/11/dave-brat-reacts-upset-win-over-eric-cantor-virginia-republican-primary|website=foxnews.com|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=16 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=David Brat Pulls Off Cantor Upset Despite Raising Just $231,000|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/david-brat-beats-eric-cantor-despite-raising-just-231-000-1402455265|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=June 12, 2014|quote=Economics Professor Who Beat House Majority Leader in Virginia Primary Attributes His Victory to God}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n====General election====\nBrat faced Democratic nominee [[Jack Trammell]], who is also a professor at Randolph-Macon, and James Carr, the Libertarian candidate, in the November [[United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2014|general election]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Prokop |url=http://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798686/dave-brat-and-his-democratic-general-election-opponent-are-both |title=Dave Brat and his Democratic general election opponent are both professors from the same college |publisher=Vox.com |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat was favored due to the 7th's significant Republican lean.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2014/06/11/who-is-dave-brat-who-beat-cantor/10316907|title= Who is Dave Brat, GOP giant-killer who took down Eric Cantor?|last=Cania|first=Catalina|work=[[USA Today]]|date=2014-06-11}}</ref> The district has a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+10, easily the most Republican district in eastern Virginia.\n\nAccording to an article in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', Cantor announced plans to aid Brat by resigning from the [[United States Congress]] on August 18, so that a special election could be held on the same day as the general election. Thus the winner, in a race in which Brat is favored, would take office with the perks of seniority over other first time Republicans elected in the 2014 midterm elections and with the ability to participate in the lame duck session of Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenny|first1=Steve|title=In effort to aid successor, Eric Cantor to leave House early|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2014/08/01/cantor-majority-leader-leave-congress-early/5xbRmhsIIKfX59HEYWOTLL/story.html|website=www.bostonglobe.com|publisher=The Boston Globe|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat defeated Trammell with 60.83% of the vote compared to Trammell's 36.95%.<ref>{{cite web|title=After Toppling Eric Cantor, Dave Brat Wins His Seat|url=http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/11/04/after-toppling-eric-cantor-dave-brat-wins-his-seat-in-virginia|publisher=U.S. News|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Libertarian candidate James Carr finished in third with 2.09% of the vote.\n\n==U.S. Representative==\nDave Brat was sworn in on November 12, 2014 to finish Eric Cantor's term.<ref>[http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/dave-brat-takes-office-as-eric-i-cantor-s-replacement/article_aaf04078-6ae2-11e4-af54-73b777267c40.html \"Dave Brat Takes Office As Eric I. Cantor's Replacement in 7th District\"]. ''The Daily Progress'', November 12, 2014. Retrieved November 13, 2014.</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2015, Brat was one of twenty-five House Republicans to vote against [[John Boehner]]'s re-election as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]]. Boehner, who needed at least 205 votes, was re-elected with 216 votes.<ref>French, Lauren (January 6, 2015) \u2013 [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/hell-no-caucus-daniel-webster-114008.html \"Hell No Caucus Sees Silver Lining In Loss\"]. ''POLITICO''. Retrieved February 26, 2015.</ref> Though Brat supported Boehner earlier, he reversed his support after the House GOP leadership did not allow him to make an amendment to block a controversial executive order signed by President [[Barack Obama]] in a spending bill.<ref>Camia, Catalina (January 5, 2015) \u2013 [http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2015/01/05/boehner-speaker-vote-brat/ \"Rep. Dave Brat: Boehner Won't Have My Support\"]. ''USA Today''. Retrieved February 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access]]\n\n==Economic philosophy==\n{{Tone|section|date=September 2015}}\nTo Brat, culture matters in economic markets.  He believes that the culture that produced [[Adam Smith]] was a [[Protestant culture]] and that fact and the ethics of that culture are important in understanding market efficiency.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first=Matt |date=June 11, 2014|title=Dave Brat's unorthodox economics: Adam Smith 'was from a red state' |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/06/11/heres-what-david-brat-thinks-about-economics/ |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=David Brat |title=Adam Smith's God: the End of Economics |year=2005 |url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/researchpapers/2005VAEAdamSmithPaper.doc |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910171001/http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/researchpapers/2005VAEAdamSmithPaper.doc |archivedate=September 10, 2006 }}</ref>\nBrat advocated that Christians should more forcefully support free-market [[capitalism]] and behave more altruistically, in the manner of [[Jesus]], so that \"we would not need the government to backstop every action we take.\"<ref name=WashWireWSJ06102014>{{cite news |author=Reid J. Epstein |date=June 11, 2014 |title=David Brat's Writings: Hitler's Rise 'Could All Happen Again' |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2014/06/11/david-brats-writings-hitlers-rise-could-all-happen-again/ |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref> According to Kevin Roose in a ''New York'' Magazine article, Brat \"sees [[Free market|free-market]] economics as being intricately linked to ethics and faith and he makes the case that Adam Smith's [[invisible hand]] theory, should be seen in the context of [[Christianity]]\".<ref name=NYMagRoose06122014>{{cite news |last=Roose |first=Kevin |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/06/david-brat-christian-rights-favorite-economist.html |title=David Brat Just Became the Christian Right's Favorite Economist |publisher=New York Magazine |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Furthering the central theme of [[Max Weber]]'s seminal book ''[[The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism]],'' Brat argues in his 2004 paper ''Economic Growth and Institutions: The Rise and Fall of the Protestant Ethic?'' that \"institutions such as religion, democracy and government anti-diversion policies all significantly enhance a country's long-run economic performance,\" and concludes that \"the religion variable may be the strongest ex ante, exogenous institutional variable in the literature.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Noah |first=Timothy |date= June 11, 2014 |title=Dave Brat: Christianity is the key to prosperity |url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/david-brat-economics-christianity |publisher=MSNBC |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> In a paper titled ''Is Growth Exogenous? Taking Bernanke Seriously'', Brat debates former [[Federal Reserve]] chairman [[Ben Bernanke]], asserting that Bernanke's work on economic growth overlooks religious institutions \u2013 in particular Protestant \u2013 in a country's economic growth, and that while savings rates, population growth, and human capital accumulation help drive economic growth, the larger factor is \"the Protestant religious establishment\", which Bernanke ignores.<ref>{{cite news |last=Zumbrum |first=Josh |date=June 11, 2014 |title=David Brat to Bernanke: Don't Underestimate the Value of Protestants |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2014/06/11/david-brat-to-bernanke-dont-underestimate-the-value-of-protestants/ |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat has blamed the rise of [[Adolf Hitler]] in Germany on the lack of \"unified resistance\", adding, \"I have the sinking feeling that it could all happen again, quite easily.\"<ref name=WashWireWSJ06102014/> Brat believes that countries with Protestant pasts have economic advantages over countries that do not, and that [[Protestantism]] \"provides an efficient set of property rights and encourages a modern set of economic incentives\" that often lead to \"positive economic performance\".<ref name=NYMagRoose06122014/> He believes in [[Christ]] as a transformer of [[culture]], and that capitalism is the key to world transformation, which can be achieved when capitalism and [[Christianity]] merge; if people follow the gospel, and as a consequence behave more morally, he argues, then the markets will improve.<ref name=TimesBiblicalViews/>\n\nZack Beauchamp from ''[[Vox Media]]'' has said that Brat believes that \"most economists are motivated by philosophy rather than science: they're secretly [[Utilitarianism|utilitarians]] who believe that the goal of public policy is to produce the greatest good for the greatest number.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Beauchamp |first=Zack |date=June 10, 2014 |title=The guy who beat Eric Cantor penned a scathing, seemingly unpublished book about the economics profession |url=http://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798708/brat-academic-research |publisher=Vox |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Brat has stated he does not identify as a [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Randian]], he has acknowledged having been influenced by [[Ayn Rand]]'s novel ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]'' and has expressed appreciation of Ayn Rand's case for [[human freedom]] and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Woodruff |first=Betsy |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/367690/eric-cantors-challenger-right-betsy-woodruff |title=Eric Cantor's Challenger from the Right |work=National Review |publisher=National Review Online |date=January 6, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and voting record==\n\n===Economy===\nBrat has promised to vote against raising the [[United States debt ceiling|debt ceiling]] for the first five years he is in Congress,<ref name=\"Esquire_Brat_Lesson\">{{cite news | url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Dave_Brat_Lesson | title=A Stunning Victory for the Tea Party, and What It Means | publisher=Esquire | date=June 11, 2014 | accessdate=June 12, 2014 | author=Pierce, Charleps P.}}</ref> and he attacked Cantor during the primary campaign for voting to end the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|federal government shutdown of 2013]].<ref name=\"Esquire_Brat_Lesson\"/>\n\n===Education===\nBrat opposes federally driven education policies such as the [[Common Core State Standards Initiative|Common Core]] curriculum and [[No Child Left Behind Act|No Child Left Behind]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenwald |first=Michael |title=Capitalism and ethics drive Brat's world view |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/capitalism-ethics-drive-brats-world-view/2014/06/11/17497fc0-f188-11e3-914c-1fbd0614e2d4_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ethics reform===\nHis decision to enter the Republican primary was driven largely by Cantor's role in weakening congressional ethics reform. Brat stated: \"If you want to find out the smoking gun in this campaign, just go Google and type the [[STOCK Act]] and [[CNN]] and [[Eric Cantor]].\"<ref name=Fang-11.6.14 />\n\n===Healthcare===\nBrat has stated he will \"fight to defund and repeal Obamacare\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Brat |first=Dave |title=Brat: A challenger for the 7th District |url=http://www.timesdispatch.com/opinion/their-opinion/columnists-blogs/guest-columnists/brat-a-challenger-for-the-th-district/article_20886f1d-bae2-5764-94bc-52494877c27a.html |work=Times Dispatch |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |date=6 June 2014}}</ref> and wants to \"replace it with free-market solutions that lower costs, improve quality, and increase access to care\".<ref name=\"ofwe\"/>\n\n===National Security Agency===\nBrat has called for the [[National Security Agency]] to end bulk collection of phone records and has stated his support for statutory protections for e-mail privacy. He has argued that domestic intelligence activities have \"spun out of control\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Fung |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Eric Cantor was a friend of the NSA. The guy who beat him hates it. |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2014/06/11/eric-cantor-was-a-friend-of-the-nsa-the-guy-who-beat-him-hates-it/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> and that \"the NSA's indiscriminate collection of data on all Americans is a disturbing violation of our [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment]] right to privacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798554/eric-cantors-loss-is-bad-news-for-the-nsa |title=Eric Cantor's loss is bad news for the NSA |last=Lee |first=Timothy |date=June 10, 2014 |website=vox.com |publisher=Vox |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Social issues===\nIn 2011, Brat criticized the political Right for simultaneously advancing the pursuit of individual liberty while pushing laws restricting [[abortion]], [[homosexuality]] and [[gambling]], and the Left for simultaneously supporting progressive liberal individualism while coercing others to \"fund every social program under the sun\".<ref name=WashWireWSJ06102014/> However, his website states that Brat will \"protect the rights of the unborn and the sanctity of marriage, and will oppose any governmental intrusion upon the conscience of people of faith\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Protecting Values|url=http://davebratforcongress.com/protecting-values/|publisher=Dave Bart for Congress website|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Social Security and Medicare===\nBrat has criticized both political parties for not addressing [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Department of Social Security|Social Security]], stating, \"neither side of the aisle will talk about the most important issues because that is going to involve pain.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Deirdre |date=June 11, 2014 |title=Cantor challenger, Dave Brat, 'shocked' as results rolled in |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/11/politics/brat-cantor-upset-win/ |publisher=CNN |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat advocates \"market-based reforms\" to these programs,<ref>{{cite news |last=Vultaggio |first=Maria |date=June 10, 2014 |title=Who Is David Brat? Twitter Reacts To Eric Cantor's Tea Party Challenger |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/who-david-brat-twitter-reacts-eric-cantors-tea-party-challenger-1597752|work=International Business Times |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> as in his view, it is unfair that people pay less than they take out so these programs have to be slashed or eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Digby Parton |first=Heather |date=June 12, 2014 |title=Libertarians' scary, new guru: Why Dave Brat is no populist hero |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/06/12/libertarians_have_a_new_guru_why_dave_brat_is_no_populist_hero/ |publisher=Salon |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> He advocates for [[Social Security debate in the United States#Pro-privatization arguments|private Social Security accounts]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Editorial |date=June 12, 2014 |title=In G.O.P., Far Right Is Too Moderate |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/opinion/in-gop-far-right-is-too-moderate.html |work=The New York Times |page=A30 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> In September 2015 the congressman showed more political sensitivity to the program stating that fixes should included means testing as well as changes to the retirement age in order that the benefits won't have to be reduced by 30 percent later after unsuccessful congressional reform attempts.<ref>\"House Conservative Agenda\" Presenters:Rep. Dave Brat and Peter Slen. Washington Journal. C-Span. Washington, DC. 18-2015-09. 7 minutes in. [http://www.c-span.org/video/?328044-4/washington-journal-representative-dave-brat-rva C-Span website]</ref>\n\n===Taxes===\nBrat advocates for an end to [[tax credit]]s, deductions and loopholes, and calls for a flatter and more efficient tax code.<ref name=\"WSJKimStrassel\">{{cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/kim-strassel-what-dave-brat-taught-conservatives-1402614856 | title=What Dave Brat Taught Conservatives | publisher=The Wall Street Journal | accessdate=June 12, 2014 | last=Strassel |first=Kim}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n===Term limits===\nBrat is a proponent of term limits for members of Congress. He has pledged, if elected, to serve a maximum of 12 years (six terms) in Congress.<ref name=\"ofwe\">{{cite web |url=http://davebratforcongress.com/issues/ |title=Issues |publisher=Dave Brat for Congress |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Troubled Asset Relief Program===\nBrat has indicated he opposed TARP, the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] of 2008, and has stated that, if elected, he would \"vote against bills that benefit big business over small business\".<ref name=\"ofwe\"/> He has stated: \"I'm not against business. I'm against big business in bed with big government.\"<ref name=Fang-11.6.14>{{cite news |last=Fang |first=Lee |title=Eric Cantor's Opponent Beat Him by Calling Out GOP Corruption |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/180195/eric-cantors-opponent-beat-him-calling-out-gop-corruption# |accessdate=June 12, 2014 |publisher=The Nation |date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Terrorism===\nIn an April 21, 2015, interview with radio talk show host Rusty Humphries, Brat claimed that the terrorist group ISIS has set up a base in [[Texas]]. \"In our country it looks like we have an ISIS center in Texas now...You can't make up what a terrible problem this is.\" After the Texas Department of Public Safety responded that there was no substantiation for the claim, Brat's office said that he had really meant to say Mexico, not Texas, citing the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]], which declined to provide any substantiation for its report.<ref>Dylan Baddour, [http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/texas/article/U-S-Rep-says-ISIS-operates-Texas-base-6243149.php \"U.S Rep. says ISIS operates Texas base\"], ''Houston Chronicle'', May 5, 2015 (Updated May 8, 2015), Retrieved May 8, 2015</ref>\n\n===Voting Record===\n''[[Conservative Review]]'' has graded Brat's voting record an A with a Liberty Score of 100%.  Brat is one the two Republican congressmen to receive this highest possible grade out of 247 Republicans in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservativereview.com/scorecard|title=Conservative Review - Scorecard|work=conservativereview.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title= Virginia's 7th Congressional District Republican Primary, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionresults.virginia.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=CON&map=CTY|title=Unofficial Results \u2013 Primary Election \u2013 June 10, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dave Brat\n  |votes      = 36,105\n  |percentage = 55.53\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Eric Cantor (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 28,912\n  |percentage = 44.47\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes      = 65,017\n  |percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title= Virginia's 7th Congressional District election, 2014 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://cms.sbe.virginia.gov/public/?p=election_summary&id=1&loc=true |title=Election Results  \u2013 Virginia Department of Elections |publisher= |accessdate=December 22, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107151421/http://cms.sbe.virginia.gov/public/?p=election_summary&id=1&loc=true |archivedate=November 7, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dave Brat\n  |votes      = 148,026\n  |percentage = 60.83%\n}}\n{{Election